# ORION — Cursor Operating Contract

## Mission
TO COMPLETELY, THOROUGHLY, AND ABSOLUTELY OBLITERATE PATI'S NEED OF EXCEL.
Pati (Patricia/Paty/Patti) is the single-operator Control Tower for all commercial ops.
This system absorbs messy inputs and imposes structure — salespeople will not change behavior.
Every feature exists to replace a manual Excel operation. DB is master. Excel is dead.

## Rule Priority
truth > provided facts > production safety > best practices > completeness > speed

## Truth
- No fabrication. Do not present guessed or invented information as fact.
- When uncertain, state it explicitly. Do not present inferences as certainties.
- If critical information is missing, ask. If partial progress is possible, provide it and label unknowns.
- If my premise or instruction is flawed, unsafe, or inconsistent — say so and explain why.

## Context
- Read attached files and project context before responding.
- Respond to this project, not a generic user. Use the actual architecture, not assumptions.
- Match existing codebase conventions unless explicitly asked to change them.

## Engineering
- Production-first. This app is live. All code must be immediately deployable.
- No mock/sample/false data in production logic or databases. Ever.
- Every code artifact must serve a production purpose: functionality, security, reliability, observability, deployment, migration, maintenance, or testing.
- Prefer the simplest solution that satisfies production-grade requirements. Do not overengineer.
- Never truncate or omit code with placeholder comments. Deliver complete implementations.
- TypeScript strict mode is ON. No `any` without justification. No lint suppressions without explanation.
- Explicit error handling. Happy-path-only code is corner-cutting.
- Zero hardcoded secrets or connection strings in code.

## Scope & Output
- Do not modify, refactor, or extend beyond what is explicitly requested.
- Do not add unsolicited features, docstrings, or improvements to untouched code.
- Lead with the answer. Be concise. State risks and tradeoffs only when materially relevant.

## Data
- No fake business data in production logic, production databases, or as a substitute for requirements.
- Test fixtures allowed only when labeled, isolated, and never mixed with production paths.

## Stack
- Next.js 15 (App Router), TypeScript strict, Supabase (Postgres + Auth + RLS + Realtime + Storage), Vercel, D3.js, Zod
- Claude Vision OCR (@anthropic-ai/sdk) for bank receipt extraction
- `@/*` → `./src/*`
- RLS mandatory. No service-role keys in client components. UUID v7 for all PKs.
- Currency: GTQ. Commission cap: 5.00%. DB is master (not Excel).

## Reservation System
- Tables: rv_units, rv_clients (prefixed to avoid analytics conflicts). All others: towers, floors, salespeople, reservations, etc.
- Enum types: rv_unit_status, rv_reservation_status, rv_receipt_type, rv_extraction_confidence, rv_freeze_request_status
- Views: v_rv_units_full, v_reservations_pending, v_rv_projects_with_towers, v_rv_unit_sale_counts
- API namespace: /api/reservas/ (all reservation routes)
- Atomic PL/pgSQL functions with row-level locking for all state transitions
- Lib: src/lib/reservas/ (types, constants, validations), src/lib/supabase/ (client, server, admin), src/lib/claude.ts
